    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Although Benjamin has a strong family history of breast cancer, the description of the mass mainly goes with a benign lesion: regular, mobile, tender, concentric with normal nipple and skin and no lymphadenopathy. A malignant mass tends to be hard, irregular, non-tender, and tethered (immobile). Moreover, the lump started to develop after spironolactone, which is infamous for drug-induced gynecomastia. These make drug-induced gynecomastia a likely diagnosis. Some medications that cause gynecomastia include antifungals, anti-androgens, calcium channel blockers, digoxin, and spironolactone. On the other hand, drug-induced gynecomastia is usually bilateral, though it can be unilateral on occasion. Benjamin is on two medications with the potential to cause breast enlargement, namely spironolactone and digoxin. Since the symptoms started after the introduction of spironolactone, it is more likely to have caused the problem. However, to err on the safe side, and as the lesion is unilateral, a breast ultrasound scan to confirm the diagnosis and exclude more sinister causes is the most appropriate action to take for Benjamin. Ultrasound is recommended as the first-line investigation in such cases. Once drug-induced gynecomastia is confirmed, the next step would be the cessation of the offending drug and observation for the resolution of the mass. In this case, however, the pros and cons of such action should be considered. Cessation of spironolactone (option B) or digoxin (option D) to which management of his CHF is dependent does not seem a wise decision. A mass biopsy using FNA (option C) would be considered to determine if the mass had suggestive features of malignancy or if the ultrasound was consistent with malignancy. Given the uncertain diagnosis, excision of the lump (option E) for cosmetic concerns will not be a priority at this stage.`,
