    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `It has been estimated that approximately 20% of all cancers are caused by excess weight. The Million Women Study, the largest study of its kind on women, has shown that approximately half of cancers can be attributed to obesity in postmenopausal women. The International Agency for Research into Cancer (IARC) and the World Cancer Research Fund (WCRF) reports show that common cancers in obese people are predominantly endometrial, esophageal adenocarcinoma, colorectal, postmenopausal breast cancer, prostate, and renal cancers. Less common malignancies associated with obesity are melanoma, thyroid cancer, leukemia, non-Hodgkin's lymphoma, and multiple myeloma. The role of obesity in the development of breast cancer in women is hypothesized to be due to increased production of endogenous estrogen in the fat tissue and excess exposure of the breast tissue to unopposed endogenous estrogen. For this patient, weight reduction is the most appropriate advice for both general health and risk reduction for breast cancer. (Option A) Smoking has a positive link to some malignancies. Some reports advocate tobacco smoking as a risk factor for the development of breast cancer; however, this risk is not as significant as obesity. (Option C) Regular exercise is associated with improved overall health and decreased incidence of malignancies. The effect does not seem to be superior to weight reduction for breast cancer. (Options D and E) The use of contraceptive pills has been associated with only a slightly increased risk of breast cancer after 5 years of use. Changing the contraception method or reducing the dose of estrogen is not likely to significantly decrease such risk.`,
