    topic: "Endocrinology",
    subtopic: "Gynecomastia - medication-induced",
    stem: `Lucas is a 67-year-old patient of yours in your GP clinic. He has congestive heart failure (CHF) diagnosed three years ago, for which he has been on carvedilol, perindopril, and digoxin with improvement in symptoms. Six months ago, due to decompensation of his CHF, evident by increased dyspnea and ankle edema, and after specialist advice, he was started on spironolactone. Today, he has presented with a complaint of painful unilateral breast enlargement. He does not smoke and drinks only on social occasions and within safe limits. His past medical history, besides the CHF, is a myocardial infarction seven years ago. His family history is remarkable for breast cancer in his mother, who died 15 years ago, and in his sister at the age of 52. On examination, you notice a left breast lump concentric with the nipple, which is firm, rubbery, and slightly tender. There is no nipple discharge, ulceration, or regional lymphadenopathy. The other breast is normal. Which of the following could be the most likely cause of this presentation?`,
