    correctAnswer: "E",
    explanation: `Nodular thyroid disease is a common clinical problem. Steps to consider in approaching a thyroid nodule and excluding malignancy include: (1) a thorough clinical evaluation, (2) thyroid function tests (TFT), and (3) an ultrasound exam of the thyroid gland and fine needle aspiration (FNA) biopsy if the nodule is larger than 1 cm. Thyroid FNA biopsy is the most accurate test for determining malignancy and is an essential and integral part of evaluating a thyroid nodule. When guided by ultrasound, the results are even more accurate. FNA results are classified as diagnostic (satisfactory) and non-diagnostic (unsatisfactory). Unsatisfactory smears, comprising 5-10% of all results, are due to the specimen's hypocellularity, usually caused by cystic fluid in the specimen, bloody smear, or inappropriate preparation. Diagnostic smears are conventionally classified as: Benign (60-70% of all reports, negative for malignancy, includes colloid nodules, cysts, or Hashimoto thyroiditis); Malignant (5% of all reports, positive for malignancy, including primary thyroid or non-thyroid metastatic cancers, with papillary carcinoma being the most common type of thyroid malignancy); and Indeterminate/atypical (10-20% of all reports, including atypical changes, Follicular neoplasms, or Hurthle cells, with 15-60% risk of malignancy, average 30%). Of these conditions, the main difficulty arises in cases of follicular neoplasm because it is impossible to distinguish a follicular adenoma (benign lesion) from a follicular carcinoma on cytological assessment. Therefore, follicular lesions often require excision and a complete examination of the lesion and its capsule before a definitive diagnosis can be made. In general, lesions with atypical features are best completely excised for a full evaluation and making a definite diagnosis. Repeating the FNA (option D) under the ultrasound guide is used in cases of non-diagnostic reports to obtain an adequate and appropriately prepared sample. (Option B) Laryngoscopy adds no diagnostic value to evaluating a nodule within the thyroid gland and is an entirely irrelevant option. CT scan (option A) or MRI (option C) are not routinely indicated in the assessment of thyroid nodules because they cannot reliably distinguish benign from malignant lesions. The main indication for a CT scan or MRI is to determine the presence and extent of retrosternal extension and the presence and degree of tracheal compression in the presence of obstructive symptoms.`,
