    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `The photograph shows bilateral discoid breast enlargement in a pubertal boy, consistent with gynecomastia as the most likely diagnosis. Gynecomastia can be physiologic or non-physiologic (pathologic). Physiologic gynecomastia has three phases of occurrence, corresponding to times of hormonal changes. The first peak occurs in the neonatal period due to the transplacental passage of estrogen. Gynecomastia of the neonate is seen in 60% to 90% of neonates and almost always resolves spontaneously within the first year of life. The second peak occurs during puberty when palpable breast tissue and an increase in breast size occur. It can present as early as ten years, but the onset peak is between the ages of 13 and 14. The incidence declines in the late teenage years. By the age of 17, only 10% of boys have persistent gynecomastia. The last peak of occurrence is in adults between the ages of 50 and 80. For a patient presenting with gynecomastia, a thorough history, including drug history and physical exam, should be undertaken to exclude pathologic causes of gynecomastia such as medications and drug abuse, hypogonadism, chronic liver or kidney disease, hyperthyroidism, tumors (e.g., testicular, adrenal) and malnutrition. In 25% of cases of gynecomastia, no identifiable cause is found (idiopathic gynecomastia). Ethan is 16 years old and has no remarkable clues in his history indicating a pathologic cause. This suggests he has pubertal gynecomastia. Pubertal gynecomastia often resolves between 6 months and two years of onset and requires no active management except explaining and reassurance. (Option A) Although medications are the cause of gynecomastia in 10 to 25% of cases, salbutamol and fluticasone (and almost none of the other asthma medications) have shown a relation with the development of gynecomastia, and advice for a change of asthma medications is not a correct option. (Option C) Mastectomy is considered for patients with persistent gynecomastia who are distressed by their breast appearance due to cosmetic reasons. (Option D) Testosterone injection may be an option for patients with hypogonadism for the general treatment of hypogonadism and not merely for gynecomastia. (Option E) Testicular cancers should be considered in younger adults presenting with pathologic gynecomastia. While some authors advocate routing use of ultrasound for detection a non-palpable testicular mass, the majority advocate routine use of this modality in patients who have abnormal scrotal exam findings such as a testicular mass, signs of feminization, and other indicators of testicular malignancies. Ethan has a provisional diagnosis of physiologic gynecomastia, and there are no clues in the history and physical examination to mandate a scrotal ultrasound.`,
