    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `"Nipple discharge" refers to fluid that can be expressed from the nipple. While it can be a normal occurrence in some situations, it can also indicate a potential underlying medical condition, particularly if it is spontaneous, unilateral, or accompanied by other breast symptoms such as a lump. Further evaluation is usually necessary to differentiate between benign and more serious conditions, such as cancer. In this patient, the green colour of the discharge and the absence of inflammatory signs and a lump make ductal ectasia the most likely diagnosis. Ductal ectasia, also known as mammary duct ectasia, is a non-cancerous breast condition that occurs when a milk duct widens and thickens. It's most common in women who are approaching or have gone through menopause. In most cases, multiple ducts are involved. Symptoms of ductal ectasia include the following: thick nipple discharge, often greenish; nipple or breast tenderness; inflammation of the clogged duct (periductal mastitis). (Option A) Carcinoma in situ typically presents with microcalcifications on imaging rather than nipple discharge. (Option C) Inflammatory breast diseases, such as mastitis, present with redness, warmth, and systemic signs of infection, none of which are present here.`,
