    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `In children with type I diabetes mellitus, hypoglycemia is the most commonly encountered complication. Hypoglycemia may lead to seizures and loss of consciousness. In childhood (other than a neonatal period), hypoglycemia is defined as a blood glucose level of <2.6 mmol/L. The most appropriate treatment for severe hypoglycemia when the patient is unconscious and unable to take oral glucose is a bolus of intravenous dextrose 10%, 2.5 to 5 mL/kg, followed by 0.03 to 0.05 mL/kg/minute until the patient is stable. In adults with hypoglycemia, 50% glucose solution treats severe hypoglycemia. This solution is not recommended for children because it can result in serum hyperosmolarity and death. In a conscious and cooperative child, the oral route is preferred.`,
