    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Currently, bisphosphonates are the first-line treatment for osteoporosis in patients with or without a history of breast cancer. Bisphosphonates do not interact with estrogen receptors. Although estrogen (Premarin) has been used for the prevention of osteoporosis in women, its use has been associated with an increased risk of breast cancer if used beyond the recommended duration of therapy (7 years). Estrogen-containing regimens are inappropriate options for patients with a personal history of breast cancer. Raloxifene is a selective estrogen receptor modulator (SERM) used to treat osteoporosis if bisphosphonates are contraindicated. It has the benefits of estrogen effects on bones without increasing the risk of estrogen-dependent cancers, i.e., breast and endometrial cancers. As a matter of fact, raloxifene reduces the risk of breast cancer in high-risk postmenopausal women. This drug is often used as the most appropriate option for treating younger postmenopausal women with only vertebral osteoporosis because it is not effective for the prevention of non-vertebral fractures. Neither raloxifene nor tamoxifen is used as a first-line medication for the treatment of osteoporosis.`,
