    explanation: `Different guidelines and authors suggest various indications for commencing medical therapy for osteoporosis. Osteoporosis is defined as a T-score equal to or less than -2.5 on BMD. Established osteoporosis is the preferred term for those with osteoporosis (T-score <-2.5 at the hip or spine) and one or more fragility fractures. A first fragility fracture doubles the risk of another fracture; with two previous fractures, there is a 12-fold increase in the risk of consequent fractures. Current guidelines recommend treating those with a fracture and a T-score below -1.5. In other words, the diagnosis of osteoporosis is not required to treat these individuals (a T-score of -2.5 is not needed to start treatment). All the following patients need medical treatment: those with a minimal trauma fracture (even if T-score is not <-2.5; a T-score of <-1.5 and a fracture necessitate medical treatment), those 70 years old or older, and those currently on prolonged high-dose corticosteroid treatment (at least 7.5 mg/day prednisolone or equivalent) and with a T-score of –1.5 or lower. For others, ensuring adequate dietary calcium and vitamin D intake (or supplementation if there is adequate dietary intake) and lifestyle modification such as exercise, reducing alcohol consumption and stopping smoking are recommended. Unless contraindicated, bisphosphonates are always the first-line option for treating osteoporosis. Although alendronate was considered the drug of choice, recent recommendations favor the use of intravenous zoledronic acid due to greater compliance. Calcium and vitamin D should be given to all patients undergoing medical treatment regardless of the specific agent.`,
